# Research: 2025-2026 SvelteKit Google OAuth options

## Summary
For a SvelteKit + Neon/Postgres + Drizzle app that needs Google OAuth plus an email allowlist/permissions, **Better Auth is the best default choice**: it is now explicitly surfaced by Svelte/SvelteKit tooling, has a SvelteKit integration, Google provider docs, and a first-party Drizzle adapter. Use **Arctic** only if you want to own all auth/session schema and keep the OAuth layer minimal; treat **Auth.js SvelteKit** as viable but less attractive for a new app because its SvelteKit package is marked experimental and Auth.js is now maintained under Better Auth.

## Findings
1. **Official SvelteKit guidance is intentionally low-level but points toward Better Auth for library setup** — SvelteKit’s auth docs say auth cookies are checked in server hooks and user data is stored in `locals`; the Svelte CLI can add Better Auth to an existing/new project, and that add-on gives “a complete auth setup for SvelteKit with Drizzle as the database adapter.” [SvelteKit auth docs](https://svelte.dev/docs/kit/auth), [Svelte CLI Better Auth add-on](https://svelte.dev/docs/cli/better-auth)
2. **Better Auth solves SvelteKit-specific plumbing gotchas** — its SvelteKit integration mounts via `svelteKitHandler` in `hooks.server.ts`, documents that `event.locals.user/session` are not populated automatically, and provides a `sveltekitCookies(getRequestEvent)` plugin so cookies are correctly set from SvelteKit server actions. [Better Auth SvelteKit integration](https://better-auth.com/docs/integrations/svelte-kit)
3. **Better Auth fits Neon/Drizzle best** — the Drizzle adapter supports PostgreSQL (`provider: "pg"`), schema/table/field mapping, generated schema/migrations, and optional joins; Neon’s own current Auth migration docs describe Neon Auth as built on Better Auth, with the database as the source of truth and isolated auth data per branch, though Neon’s SDK docs are mostly Next/React-oriented and marked beta. [Better Auth Drizzle adapter](https://better-auth.com/docs/adapters/drizzle), [Neon Auth with Better Auth](https://neon.tech/docs/neon-auth/quick-start/drizzle)
4. **Better Auth Google OAuth covers common Google gotchas** — docs call out `baseURL`/`BETTER_AUTH_URL` to prevent `redirect_uri_mismatch`, the exact `/api/auth/callback/google` redirect URI, account-selection prompts, requesting extra scopes, and Google’s refresh-token behavior (`accessType: "offline"`, `prompt: "select_account consent"`, first-consent limitation). [Better Auth Google provider](https://www.better-auth.com/docs/authentication/google)
5. **Auth.js SvelteKit is convenient but less compelling for a greenfield 2026 SvelteKit app** — it is the official Auth.js SvelteKit integration and includes SvelteKit actions/components, session helpers, route protection guidance, lazy initialization, and an official Drizzle adapter. But the docs mark `@auth/sveltekit` as experimental, and Better Auth announced in 2025 that Auth.js is now maintained/overseen by the Better Auth team; Better Auth’s migration docs also say there is “no urgent need” to migrate if Auth.js already works, implying stability for existing apps rather than strongest new-project default. [Auth.js SvelteKit](https://authjs.dev/reference/sveltekit), [Auth.js Drizzle adapter](https://authjs.dev/getting-started/adapters/drizzle), [Auth.js joins Better Auth](https://better-auth.com/blog/authjs-joins-better-auth), [Auth.js to Better Auth migration](https://better-auth.com/docs/guides/next-auth-migration-guide)
6. **Arctic is the smallest and most explicit option, not a full auth system** — Arctic is a typed, runtime-agnostic OAuth 2.0 client library, not session/user/permissions management. Its Google docs cover state, PKCE code verifier, ID token decoding, `email` scope, refresh tokens, and token revocation; Lucia’s SvelteKit tutorial shows the manual pieces you must implement: OAuth routes, state/code-verifier cookies, user lookup/creation, session creation, and session-cookie invalidation. [Arctic docs](https://arcticjs.dev/), [Arctic Google provider](https://arcticjs.dev/providers/google), [Lucia Google OAuth in SvelteKit](https://lucia-auth.com/tutorials/google-oauth/sveltekit)
7. **Email allowlist/permissions are straightforward in either Better Auth or Arctic, but at different layers** — with Better Auth, enforce allowlist/roles around signup/sign-in callbacks/hooks and store app permissions in your own Drizzle tables keyed to Better Auth users; this keeps session/cookie/OAuth details outsourced. With Arctic, check the decoded Google `email`/`email_verified` claims before creating a user/session and design all user/role/session tables yourself; this is simpler conceptually but more code and more security surface.

